<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>do a job on someone • do the job for someone</xh5><p> <i>do a job on someone</i>—(sl.) 1. treat smb. roughly; injure or harm a person: There’s no need to <u>do a job on me</u>, man, I’ll tell you everything I know. <b>2. </b><i>(also: do a snow job on someone)</i> take advantage of a person, especially by persuasion or deception: My local friendly plumber <u>did a job on me</u> cleaning out my drain.</p><p> <i>do the job for someone</i>—<i>(also: do the business for someone)</i> accomplish one’s purpose; achieve the desired result: When he couldn’t get whiskey he would drink lemon or vanilla extract. It was mostly alcohol, so it <u>did the job for him</u>.</p> </entry>
